text:
Lag reduction:
Active (Powered) HDMI splitter. Output A goes to the capture card. Output B goes to a viewing device (TV, monitor, etc)
Then you can just play the game from the device connected to output B. This should pretty much eliminate 90% of the lag.

Optional:
You can then further reduce lag by getting a high-response monitor. Most monitors have <5ms delay (the time it takes for visuals to update). This is fine for general purpose stuff, but it could introduce input lag for people who require insanely precise inputs (like rhythm games require sometimes). Basically, the visuals you see on the screen would be up to 5ms (milliseconds) behind what it should be. So in a rhythm game, you're inputs are already going to be up to 5ms slower by default, just by using this type of display. And that's before any user input error. 

There are lots of gaming monitors with <1ms delay that would virtually eliminate any lag what so ever. You'd be swimming in full combos.

text:
Here's a few tip for anyone starting project diva, although you can use this on another rhythm game:
>Don't look at the shape as you seeing it moves to hit it as you go, but anticipate the current shape/beat, hitting them, while looking at the incoming shape. Rinse and repeat.
>Learn the pattern of the lyrics and how the vocaloid are singing
>and use that pattern as a guide
>In this, gura modified the hit prompt noise as a drum beat, which is a good audio feedback for you to anticipate your beat.
You can  pick yout own button hit prompt, to suit your style, which helps a lot.
>And whatever you do don't get nervous if you miss prob several beats, but if you did. Recuperate and just hit whatever shape that you can and continue (Don't worry about failing, it's just a game and eventually you git gud)
>have fun

Hope that helps and Happy Rhythming!
